Ch. VII (p. 94—110) attacks the Archdeacons, their pride and luxury, the slight fines that they inflicted for sins in order to get more money, and especially the abuse of excommunication and absolution. Excommunication, whether active or passive, may be right or wrong according as both the sentence and the motive agree or do not agree with God's law, but excommunication with bell, book and candle is to be utterly condemned. There follows a rather fine— drawn parallel between this practice and the doctrine of Transub- stantiation.
